The courtroom the next morning felt like a pressure chamber. The air was still, recycled, tasting of lemon polish and anxiety. Every seat was filled, a murmur of voices like distant machinery underlying the formal hush. The Zyloxen panic had turned their case into a circus, and the spectators were a mix of press, public health ghouls, industry watchers, and a smattering of patient advocates who looked at Elara with betrayed eyes.

Arthur Vance sat in the very back row, in the shadows of the public gallery. He wore a plain grey overcoat, looking like any other observer, but his presence was a stone in Elara’s shoe. He was a ghost at the feast, a living reminder of the precedent she was trying to shatter.

Judge Morrow took the bench, her face an impassive mask. “Counselors, are we ready to proceed with closing arguments?”

“The plaintiffs are, Your Honor,” Elara said, rising. Her suit felt like armor, but heavy, ill-fitting.

“The defense is ready,” intoned Veridian’s lead counsel, a sleek man named Croft.

Croft went first. He was elegant, reasonable, a master of the subtle smear. He walked the jury through the “undisputed facts”—the old, lawful settlements, the good-faith reliance on regulatory standards of the time. He painted Veridian as a company of scientists and engineers, not villains, navigating the complex, evolving landscape of public health.

Then, with surgical precision, he inserted the knife.

“And when concerns were raised internally,” Croft said, hands clasped, a picture of collegial regret, “Veridian did what any responsible corporation does. It sought legal counsel. It relied on the best advice available—advice from one of the most respected environmental lawyers of his generation. Advice that the prior settlements were valid, that the matter was closed. The law, ladies and gentlemen, encourages us to rely on the advice of counsel. To now punish Veridian for following that advice… is to punish a company for following the law.”

He didn’t say Arthur’s name. He didn’t have to. Every eye in the room flicked to the back row, then to Elara. The shift was masterful, almost imperceptible: from corporate malfeasance to a tragic chain of good-faith decisions. The villain, he implied, wasn’t in the boardroom; he was sitting in the gallery, or perhaps, by association, standing at the plaintiff’s table.

By the time Croft sat down, the jury looked thoughtful, some nodding faintly. The paranoia in the room shifted, its target blurring. Elara felt it coiling around her, the insidious suggestion that she was the puppet of a guilty man, chasing a vendetta, not justice.

Judge Morrow nodded to her. “Ms. Thorne?”

Elara stood. For a moment, the courtroom swam. The faces of the jury blurred into a pale, waiting wall. The weight of the list in her briefcase—the Dalton Creek list—felt like a lodestone. She walked slowly to the lectern, placing nothing on it. She would need no notes.

“Good faith.”

She let the words hang, echoing slightly in the quiet.

“Reliance on counsel. The standards of the time.” She looked at each juror, making eye contact, holding it for a heartbeat too long. “These are the shields of power. Polished, legal, respectable. They sound so reasonable. They’re designed to.”

